<center><div class="typewriter">
  <h1>CURIOSITY</h1>
</div>

<div style="width: 670px">
One of the strongest emotions that a human can feel is curiosity. Naturally, upon finding something new, we will have an urge to explore it.

Now, something that remains constant is that curiosity is neutral. Whether it is good or bad, it all depends on the occasion. What will determine its effect is not natural but ambiguous. 

Say you hear a thud in the room across. You have two options: investigate or stay put. Now, if you decide to investigate, many things can happen. It could be something as simple as a box that fell down. But it could also be a [[Entity 8|Hound]], already eyeing its next prey. That is the duality of curiosity.

The Backrooms is a place of mystery. It is not home, but it looks ''eerily'' similar. Many aspects of it you've already seen. Halls, bedrooms, cities, fields...

Yet, the curiosity one feels here is stronger than it is naturally. One of the aspects that has carried on to this reality is outer space. At this point, the line between liminal and paranormal starts to blur. You see things you've never seen before, even if they were always right above you, in plain sight. Yet the sensation carries on; you are not safe. 

When suddenly the surface starts to redden, oxygen levels deplete, and a searing sensation fills your body, your first instinct is to report to the base. But as things become futile, your options run out. You may scream, but no noise will come out, as air is needed for sound to travel. The vacuum devours your voice completely, and slowly, you realize in your last moments that curiosity is a trickster. A cruel one, too.<br>

[[File:bloodpaintedmoon.jpg|center|301px|link= ]]<br>

As your suit scorches and your helmet becomes charred, only contrasted by the red, immolated pulp within, you decide perhaps dying mauled by a Hound is not as bad as it sounds.
</div></center>

{{Underline|FFFFFF}}{{Blurquote|image=Nightbg.png|font-size=21|quote-text='''"The Backrooms is an anomaly we can't quite comprehend. We can only pretend to understand it. Life is uncertain, and in such a perpetual world, the best we can do is to try and adapt to it. We should consider ourselves lucky we can have technology this sophisticated under these conditions. However, conventional exploration cannot tame certain levels. Some are shrouded in the mystery of outer space, the same one that you may have experienced back home. Where space shuttles once took off, we reside. And our duty is to bring light to the dark vacuums where true stars can't shine. Infinity is exhausting, but it is the precise amount of time we need to step foot where no man can."'''|person=Griss, Apollo-Infinite Leader}}<br>

