<center><div class="typewriter">
  <h1>INFINITY</h1>
</div>

<div style="width: 670px">
<center>
The moment you set foot here, the outcome is decided.<br>
Those who enter this peculiar place originating from Earth, have two phases of life:
Life before the Backrooms, and after. There is no in between.

It is truly tragic. To have your existence so susceptible to one step. One breath. That miniscule chance of you trespassing the bounds of your own reality.
There is no escape to this place, even in death. You are here for '''infinity'''.

...

Infinity.
Just like curiosity. It is a very subjective, even deceptive word.
You may know infinity as immeasurability. A moment that never ends, an eternal lapse that can either dominate lifetimes or pass in the blink of an eye. 
But it is not that complex.

For someone, infinity could last seconds. Hours. Days. Weeks. Years. Infinity means perpetuality; something that doesn't change. There is no mutable value you can possibly assign to infinity.

But to you, what is infinity?
'''''Have you experienced infinity?'''''
<br>



It is a big day for the world. This marked the day that humanity, for the first time, would try to exit familiarity. To step beyond the safety of home, and touch the skies.
You and your colleagues have been waiting for this moment. Studying their entire lives, training hard, learning strategies, overthinking in the voids left behind by curiosity, the ''unknown.''

[[File:FireCrew.png|300px|center|link= ]]
<br>

You've personally seen the very process. Engineers, scientists, working for years on end trying to create the perfect invention. A machine that could defy the binds chaining you to the very world. 

But your allies knew the deliberate truth beneath the grand occasion. For there is always an ulterior motive. A conflict. Perhaps a ''race''. A race to see who could make it farthest into the vacuum, into the pitch black '''cold''' only pierced by dots of light far from reach. Perhaps a ''war'', even.

If you knew, what was the push to continue? What was the intention? Would your suffering, your sweat, your efforts be worth it? Would the final, big launch go down in history?

Don't bother asking. For you know the truth. Every event you do won't always change history, but it will ''always'' change ''your'' history. That was the point, wasn't it?

'''''Wasn't it?'''''


<div style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);border:5px solid #1a2440; border-radius: 18px; padding: 30px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; margin-bottom: 4px;"><div style="color:#FFFFFF"><div style="font-size:20px; font-family: 'Interstate' ">
'''"FLAMES!"'''
</div></div></div>
<br>

Suddenly, you smell ''smoke''.
In that moment you stopped to think, a heat had spread across the tight shuttle. You could feel your insides already boiling, but most suffocating was the smoke. Immediately, your first instinct was to speak through the communications. Surely there was an issue.

But instead of your collected voice, came a cough. And even you yourself could hear the desperation in that mere reflex.

[[File:ApolloFire.jpg|320px|center|link= ]]
<br>

It couldn't be that. You saw it yourself. This was an invention on a scale no man had a ever seen. A meticulous craft. You wondered; '''do perfect things burst into flames faster?'''


<div style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);border:5px solid #1a2440; border-radius: 18px; padding: 30px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; margin-bottom: 4px;"><div style="color:#FFFFFF"><div style="font-size:20px; font-family: 'Interstate' ">
'''"We got a fire in the cockpit!"'''
</div></div></div>
<br>

They were screaming. Panic. You were zoned out amidst your thoughts.

How long would it take you to realize? How long until you feel panic? Until you feel the searing heat pour into every crevice? Your friends were banging against the tight, steel walls, the noise was enough, the smell was enough, the pain was more than enough.

They were trying to escape. But did it matter? We were in the air. The cockpit was on fire. And the doors were locked tight, with hard steel, crafted that way because this was the price of safety. The price of being the crew that would supposedly would set foot on the cosmos. From the beginning, this was a risky endeavor. And you, and they, knew it.

So why were we screaming? ''Why were we so surprised?''


<div style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);border:5px solid #1a2440; border-radius: 18px; padding: 30px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; margin-bottom: 4px;"><div style="color:#FFFFFF"><div style="font-size:20px; font-family: 'Interstate' ">
'''"We have a bad fire!"'''
</div></div></div>
<br>

Now came the true question.

Are you a fool? Did you think this was going to be safe? There is a reason we have fear. There is a reason our instinct tells us to stay where we are safe. Joining this mission, no matter how it felt, meant you were devoting not to a job, but your ''life''. Your ''legacy''.

Will it petrify over and lose its soul? Or will it shrivel up and burn?

[[File:WhiteBurns.jpg|290px|center|link= ]]
<br>

You can't think how. The only thing clear is the orange, reddish light slowly intensifying. The guttural screams of agony.

The shuttle was compact, trapping all of the smoke into a dense, burning, pocket. Breathing was hard. Even thinking was hard. You felt like an animal. Thrashing for survival in a position where surviving is impossible, only delayals. They determine how long you will burn, how long you will suffer.


<div style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);border:5px solid #1a2440; border-radius: 18px; padding: 30px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; margin-bottom: 4px;"><div style="color:#FFFFFF"><div style="font-size:20px; font-family: 'Interstate' ">
'''"We're burning up!"'''
</div></div></div>
<br>

You tried reaching towards the one who was nearest to you. You managed to, but you didn't even know who it was. The suit hid his face, and where you could tell by appearance the fire had molten them to incomprehension. Not like you could make them out even if they were recognizable, your mind was almost vegetative by now.

But they didn't respond. They were stiff, motionless, the only thing you felt was a mix of charred cloth and molten flesh.

The communications were destroyed, too. You realized, in the whole disaster, you hadn't uttered a single word. Why? You were the leader, after all. In the photos, you stood in the center. When you 3 converged, you took the front. When the stakes fell to one, it was you. It counted on you. But was there any word you could say? Anything you could do, that wasn't another lie? Another blurt of pain to rub salt in the wound?

You couldn't even look at their eyes. The suit covered that too. But you could imagine them perfectly; widened, erratic. The only benefit to this predicament. And for the other one, you knew dead cold what you would see. Only lucky they wore those silly helmets.


<div style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);border:5px solid #1a2440; border-radius: 18px; padding: 30px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; margin-bottom: 4px;"><div style="color:#FFFFFF"><div style="font-size:20px; font-family: 'Interstate' ">
'''"AAAAHH!!"'''
</div></div></div>
<br>

What a pity. You'd thought this would be the last thing you'd hear from him. A pathetic scream. But it was. Not because they'd perish, but because it'd be their last moments of humanity.


[[File:RogueBurns.png|290px|center|link= ]]
<br>

Eventually, even he stopped struggling.

Only you remained. 

Or so you thought.

In your clear thoughts, you managed to make out the incident. The fire had originated from below your seat. You were already dead. The first to perish, in fact. But you could've of sworn you moved your hand. That you could think. That you could make out the burning shapes and the molten corpses.

Was this just luck? No, consequence? Why couldn't you close your eyes? Why couldn't you fall stiff? The hatch could be opened from the inside, but it was designed to seal tight. It was meant for a vacuum, after all. But under the pressure of fire, it became impossible to budge. The cabin was a 100% oxygen environment; exactly what the fire preys on. Even materials once thought non-flammable ignited instantly. Almost as if it was a deliberate death trap, a blast-off not to space, but to hell. 


<div style="background: rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.3);border:5px solid #1a2440; border-radius: 18px; padding: 30px 20px; margin: 5px 10px; margin-bottom: 4px;"><div style="color:#FFFFFF"><div style="font-size:20px; font-family: 'Interstate' ">
'''"Ah, crew, can you egress at this time?"'''
</div></div></div>
<br>

Then came you.

[[File:GrissBurns.png|center|300px|link= ]]
<br>

The last thing you'd hear was the cut-off sentence and gasp of the pad leader as he opened the hatch to a...<br>


..empty cabin.



You woke up.

You were expecting oblivion, but the first noise you heard was the hum of fluorescent lights.

You opened your eyes to a sick, yellow tone.

The entire incident had unfolded not in hours, but in 30 seconds. Out of those 30 seconds, it took 15 seconds for the entire crew to "perish." 

'''''That is the duality of infinity.'''''

...

But even then, you succeeded, didn't you?

Wasn't this your mission? To exit the familiarity of your world?

It was definitely not what you expected,

but it was more than enough for a new beginning.


